                                "start": 0,
                                "stop": 9.741,
                                "byte_start": 105472,
                                "byte_stop": 144447,
                                "text": "Justice Breyer has our opinion in case 11-9307, Henderson versus United States."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 9.741,
                        "stop": 205.992,
                        "byte_start": 144447,
                        "byte_stop": 929374,
                        "speaker": {
                            "ID": 15139,
                            "name": "Stephen G. Breyer",
                            "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/people\/stephen_g_breyer",
                            "last_name": "Breyer",
                            "roles": [
                                {
                                    "id": 2785,
                                    "type": "scotus_justice",
                                    "date_start": 775890000,
                                    "date_end": 0,
                                    "appointing_president": "Bill Clinton",
                                    "role_title": "Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "institution_name": "Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/preson_role\/scotus_justice\/2785"
                                }
                            ],
                            "thumbnail": {
                                "id": 32682,
                                "mime": "image\/png",
                                "size": 49908,
                                "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/sites\/default\/files\/stephen_g_breyer_0.png"
                            },
                            "length_of_service": 7777,
                            "identifier": "stephen_g_breyer"
                        },
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 9.741,
                                "stop": 21.565,
                                "byte_start": 144447,
                                "byte_stop": 191781,
                                "text": "The federal appeals court normally will not consider a legal error that has made by a criminal trial court unless the defendant first brought the error to the trial court\u0027s attention."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 21.565,
                                "stop": 29.689,
                                "byte_start": 191781,
                                "byte_stop": 224277,
                                "text": "But Federal Rule of Criminal Procedure 52(b) creates an exception or a \u201cplain error.\u201d"
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 29.689,
                                "stop": 39.228,
                                "byte_start": 224277,
                                "byte_stop": 262416,
                                "text": "It says a federal appeals court may -- may consider a plain error even though it was not brought to the trial court\u0027s attention."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 39.228,
                                "stop": 60.702,
                                "byte_start": 262416,
                                "byte_stop": 348306,
                                "text": "Now, supposed that the time of trial, a ruling was legally questionable, but it wasn\u0027t plainly erroneous and supposed forwarded that the defendant\u0027s lawyer did not question that ruling, supposed that after the trial but before the appeal, the relevant law becomes clarified perhaps through a decision of this Court."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 60.702,
                                "stop": 73.809,
                                "byte_start": 348306,
                                "byte_stop": 400760,
                                "text": "So that by the time of the appeal, it is clear that the ruling, as of the time of appeal, was plainly erroneous but the error was not plain at the time of trial."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 73.809,
                                "stop": 78.42,
                                "byte_start": 400760,
                                "byte_stop": 419255,
                                "text": "Does the Federal Rule allow the Appeals Court to consider it?"
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 78.42,
                                "stop": 80.77,
                                "byte_start": 419255,
                                "byte_stop": 428554,
                                "text": "That is the question before us."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 80.77,
                                "stop": 93.384,
                                "byte_start": 428554,
                                "byte_stop": 479023,
                                "text": "Do the rules\u0027 words plain error, encompass errors that are not plain until the time of appeal by which time they are not plain?"
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 93.384,
                                "stop": 121.691,
                                "byte_start": 479023,
                                "byte_stop": 592290,
                                "text": "Now, the rules\u0027 language does not tell us, but in an earlier case, Johnson v. United States, we held that the rule did encompass errors that were not plain until the time of appeal when the lawyer\u0027s objection before the trial court would have seen pointless because the law at that time seemed to be so much indeed clearly in the trial court\u0027s favor."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 121.691,
                                "stop": 130.991,
                                "byte_start": 592290,
                                "byte_stop": 629488,
                                "text": "It would be anomalous, we think, to remit a Court of Appeals to consider what is now but was not -- it was now a plain-error they could consider it."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 130.991,
                                "stop": 132.355,
                                "byte_start": 629488,
                                "byte_stop": 634922,
                                "text": "Everybody agrees."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 132.355,
                                "stop": 136.741,
                                "byte_start": 634922,
                                "byte_stop": 652476,
                                "text": "When the trial court was plainly wrong, that\u0027s the ordinary case."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 136.741,
                                "stop": 145.844,
                                "byte_start": 652476,
                                "byte_stop": 688943,
                                "text": "And when the trial court was plainly right, that\u0027s the Johnson case, but not consider it when the law was not clear at the time of trial."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 145.844,
                                "stop": 147.753,
                                "byte_start": 688943,
                                "byte_stop": 696571,
                                "text": "That\u0027s the present case."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 147.753,
                                "stop": 150.234,
                                "byte_start": 696571,
                                "byte_stop": 706497,
                                "text": "Pleading those differently would be anomalous."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 150.234,
                                "stop": 164.251,
                                "byte_start": 706497,
                                "byte_stop": 762504,
                                "text": "And for this reason and for other reasons set out in our opinion, we find that the words plain-error in the rule include errors that are plain at the time of appeal even though they were not plain before."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 164.251,
                                "stop": 184.119,
                                "byte_start": 762504,
                                "byte_stop": 842021,
                                "text": "Our holding does not mean that Courts of Appeals will automatically find in the appellant\u0027s favor because there are other hurdles the appellant must overcome, including a requirement that the error affects substantial rights and that the error seriously affect the fairness integrity or public reputation of judicial proceedings."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 184.119,
                                "stop": 188.257,
                                "byte_start": 842021,
                                "byte_stop": 858530,
                                "text": "In this case, however, the Court of Appeals held it couldn\u0027t proceed further."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 188.257,
                                "stop": 193.843,
                                "byte_start": 858530,
                                "byte_stop": 880891,
                                "text": "It just could not consider an error then plain because it was not plain at the time of trial."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 193.843,
                                "stop": 199.378,
                                "byte_start": 880891,
                                "byte_stop": 903043,
                                "text": "We reversed that determination and we remand the case for further proceedings."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 199.378,
                                "stop": 205.992,
                                "byte_start": 903043,
                                "byte_stop": 929374,
                                "text": "Justice Scalia has filed a dissenting opinion in which he is enjoined by Justice Thomas and Justice Alito."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
